Ecological remarks. A mountain saproxylic species, occurs mainly in the belts of mountain forests, sporadically (
Stach 1951
) in dwarf mountain-pine shrubs (subalpine belt). It prefers shady and humid forests e.g. stands of beech, fir and spruce. Found predominantly in humid rotting wood and under bark of decaying logs, but also in litter with fine woody debris. Moreover, a numerous specimens were observed on roots of a newfallen spruce (W.M. Weiner pers. comm.). First instars were collected in April, May and Jule.
